alternatives.transcript: Hi there. In this video, we are going to learn about the RM command, stands for remove, and it will permanently remove files or folders from your system. So you do have to be a little bit careful with the the r m command. There's no trash can and there's no, way to really get back unless you use the backup directory, which means that you may have something from the previous day. But if you're working on a file that's an hour old and you remove it, well, it's gone forever. So you have to be a little bit careful. Let's see what we can do. In this folder here, we have some folders and some files. Let's say that I don't want file one dot txt anymore. So I can just type rm file one dot txt which stands for remove file one and then the nice thing about the myth system is it asks you if you are sure you wanna do that and I can type yes and it's gone. So that file is gone forever And unless I have it in my backup somewhere or somewhere else it's gone. So you have to be a little bit careful there. Now, I also have some other folders in here so let's do assign twenty three. So that's a directory and if I just type r m assign twenty three, it will say, I can't remember that, it's a directory. So what you can do is you can say r m dash r assign twenty three and that will recursively go into assignment twenty three and ask you for each file if you wanna do each file, right? And that's kind of painful if you wanted to do that, but it's and then it goes into other directories and so forth and you just have to keep hitting Y to do this. There we go and I hit Y too many times. Let's do this. Let's copy dash r assign zero to assign 23. So let's recreate the assign 23 folder and let's do it a slightly different way so we don't have to hit y all these times. Now what you can do is you can say rm rf for force and then I can do assign 23 and oops assign 23 and it will remove all the folders or all the files and folders underneath that and it will remove the assign 20 three directory. So notice there's no assign 23 directory. Now this dash r f notice it didn't ask me, prompt me for anything and it just did it. You have to be very very careful. If you are on your own system and you type something like r m r f slash that would go and remove as many files as it could throughout your entire system. Now, luckily most of the files in slash are root access only, which means you can't actually access them, but this would be a very very bad command. So you have to be very careful when you use dash r f because it's helpful and that it doesn't prompt you for every file, but you just have to know exactly when you're using it. What if I had done this? If I had done RM -RF assignments and then forgot to do like and then I did assignment assign zero and I forgot the slash in there, it would go and remove everything in the assignments folder and then try to remove everything in the assign zero folder but that's already not even there and so forth. That would be very very bad. So you have to be very careful when you use the r m command. There's another choice if you have a directory that's empty. Let's try 23 again. So now assign twenty three happens to be completely empty. You can also just type instead of r m dash r assign twenty three which would work and it would ask you if you wanna do that. You can also type r m d I r assign 23 and it just says oh look if it's an empty directory I can remove it immediately and that's how that works. So that's the RM command. Thanks.
